<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-29 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Russell Gill had to squeeze it in between
Mahler's Ninth and ``The Damnation of Faust,'' but the Columbus
Symphony musician still managed to make 50 trips up central Ohio's
tallest building.
   ``He climbed 41,751 stairs. That's one more than last year,''
said Gill's wife, Gail, after he completed his climbs.
   The string bass player's effort at the 40-story James Rhodes
State Office Tower raised about $6,000 for the Cystic Fibrosis
Foundation, said event organizers.
   The fund-raiser, in its eighth year, fell on one of the
37-year-old musician's busier weekends.
   Gill's weekend schedule included a Saturday night concert
featuring Gustav Mahler's Ninth Symphony and a Sunday afternoon
rehearsal for Hector Berlioz' ``Faust.'' So he took a half-hour nap
after the concert and started the 629-foot ascents at 2 a.m. Sunday,
finishing by about 1 p.m., his wife said.
   ``That's dedication,'' said Ann Pfau, executive director of
Cystic Fibrosis Foundation's central Ohio chapter. The rest of the
event's approximately 80 participants showed up at 10 a.m., she
said. They quit about 3:30 p.m.
   Last year's climb raised about $12,000 for the foundation, she
said. This year's goal was $15,000. Each participant in the climb
had sponsors who pledged donations to the charity.
   Participants who finished their climbs were treated to free leg
massages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to race 40,000 rubber ducks down the
White River to raise money for a food bank has been sunk by concerns
about Indiana's gambling laws.
   The state attorney general's office and private attorneys advised
organizers the event would be considered an illegal lottery, but
organizers hope state lawmakers will pass legislation enabling the
Great American Rubber Duck Race, originally scheduled for April, to
go off by September.
   Gleaner's Food Bank Inc. of Indiana has intended to sell numbered
ducks for $10 each and raise $400,000 for transporting food across
the state. The first 15 ducks across the finish line would have
brought prizes.
   J. Bradford Senden, an organizer, said each $10 donation would
have moved 65 pounds of food through the system serving 825 agencies
in Indiana.
   ``A rubber duck race is the sort of fun, harmless, family event
that can be a tremendous benefit to a charity's serious,
people-helping agenda,'' Senden said in announcing the postponement.
``It was simply an effort to make sure smaller agencies throughout
the state get food with no transportation costs.''
   With lottery proposals now circulating in the Statehouse, Senden
said he was confident provisions would be made for events like the
rubber duck race.
</TEXT>
