<FIRST>u a AM-Livestock-Arson     01-29 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Livestock-Arson,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Livestock Auction House Burns; Caller Claims Responsibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous caller who said he was a member
of an environmental extremist group claimed responsibility for a
fire Sunday that destroyed half of a rural warehouse used for
livestock auctions.
   Damage to the Dixon Livestock Auction Co. building, which
contained no animals, was estimated at $250,000, said Fire Chief
Rick Dorris. The early-morning fire was brought under control about
20 minutes after firefighters arrived.
   ``We've never been bothered by any radical groups before; we've
never received any threats,'' said Jim Schene of Stockton, whose
family rents the building and receives commissions for approximately
$10 million in livestock sold there each year.
   A man who identified himself only as a member of Earth First!
claimed responsibility for the fire in a telephone call to The
Associated Press bureau in San Francisco just before 11 a.m. The
caller did not give any reasons for the vandalism.
   Calls to other members of Earth First! were not returned Sunday.
   The unidentified caller also claimed responsibility for graffiti
at the California Cattlemen's Association, California Wool Growers
Association and the Agricultural Council of California near the
State Capitol in Sacramento. Dixon is about 20 miles west of
Sacramento.
   Spray-painted in green paint on the building housing the
associations were: ``Earth First! Agri-Bus kills,'' `Agribusiness
kills the (a drawing of the earth),'' and ``Earth First!''
   Written on the windows in what looked like shaving cream were
``Livestock Destroy,'' ``Stop Welfar,'' and ``Ran.''
   Earth First! is a radical environmental group founded by David
Foreman of Tuscon, Ariz. Militant members of the group, who often
call themselves the ``Monkeywrench Gang,'' have in the past promoted
tree spiking and destruction of equipment as ways to stop lumber
harvests.
   Tree spiking, which can damage and destroy saw blades and cause
major injuries to workers, has plagued the lumbermen along the West
Coast for several years.
   The Dixon Livestock Auction has not been involved in any recent
environmental disputes, according to local authorities.
</TEXT>
