<FIRST>r i BC-Obit-PanchenLama     01-29 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Obit-Panchen Lama,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibet's Second-Highest Religious Leader Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panchen Lama, Tibet's second-highest religious
leader and the mountain region's leading spokesman with the Chinese
government, died Saturday night, an official report said Sunday. He
was 50.
   The state-run Xinhua News Agency said the Buddhist priest died of
a sudden heart attack at the Tibetan town of Xigaze, where he was
attending ceremonies for the opening of a new stupa containing the
remains of past panchen lamas.
   The Panchen Lama, who chose to stay and support the Chinese when
the Dalai Lama fled to India in 1959 after a failed uprising, was
also a vice-chairman of the National People's Congress, China's
parliament.
   The Dalai Lama, Tibet's traditional spiritual and political
leader, has demanded the Chinese grant domestic autonomy to the
region, which communist forces overran in 1950. The Panchen Lama has
supported the Chinese.
   China claims Tibet has been Chinese territory for the past seven
centuries. In an interview with the China Daily in September, the
Panchen Lama said he had talked by telephone with the Dalai Lama and
his relations with Tibet's spiritual leader were like those between
``brothers of the same faith.''
   The Dalai Lama denied any telephone contact with the Panchen Lama.
</TEXT>
