<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-TrotskyReunion Bjt   01-29 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trotsky Reunion, Bjt,0968</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leon Trotsky's Grandchildren Reunited After 57 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY87</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two grandchildren of Leon Trotsky found each
other after 57 years, and the reunion eased a dark legacy of
intrigue and violence that shaped their lives as surely as it did
Soviet history.
   ``We were a little like two shipwrecked sailors who meet on a
beach'' after a storm, Esteban Volkow Bronstein said in an interview
after returning from a visit to his half sister, Alexandra
Zaharnovna, in Moscow.
   They were parted by dictator Josef Stalin's bloody purges and his
bitter power struggle with Trotsky, a comrade of Lenin in the
Bolshevik revolution who had commanded the Red Army.
   Stalin sent family members to exile, prison camps or the grave.
He had Trotsky exiled and his name expunged from Soviet history
books, then killed at his modest home in Mexico City by an assassin
who used a mountaineer's ice ax.
   Volkow, 62, came to live with Trotsky in the 1930s and didn't
know Alexandra was alive until he got a telephone call from French
historian Pierre Broue in November. Broue, who had just visited the
Soviet Union, said she was alive but ill.
   Volkow had seen her last in 1931, when he and their mother were
expelled from the Soviet Union. He had a friend write some phrases
in Russian and called her.
   ``Dearest sister,'' he said into the crackling telephone. ``Your
little brother Esteban sends you an embrace, a warm embrace. I don't
speak Russian.''
   Alexandra, 65 and bedridden, replied in a voice weakened by a
long struggle with cancer.
   ``She spoke with much emotion, but I couldn't understand what she
said,'' he told the interviewer. ``I kept reading the phrases,
talking and talking and repeating my phrases. Finally I said `do
svidania,' goodbye. This was the call.''
   He went to the Soviet Embassy the next day and had a visa in 72
hours. Weeks later, he and his wife underwent what he described as
an ``extremely meticulous'' clearance at customs in Moscow.
   ``Maybe they thought we were subversives,'' he said with a slight
chuckle.
   Stalin accused Trotsky of subversion when their power struggle
began in the 1920s. The assassin struck in 1940, when Trotsky had
been an exile for 11 years.
   Volkow was 14 and still remembers his beloved grandfather lying
on the floor, blood pouring from the ugly ax wounds in his head. He
keeps the house as a museum and the interview was conducted there.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of openness and
reform, a cautious reassessment of Trotsky's historical role has
begun in the Soviet Union.
   Journalists and historians no longer call him a traitor to the
revolution, and a newspaper recently agreed with foreign historians
that Stalin had Trotsky killed. The Soviet Supreme Court has
rehabilitated his son Sergei, who was executed in a prison camp.
   Alexandra knew little about their grandfather and nothing of his
murder in Mexico, Volkow said.
   ``There is no information on Leon Trotksy'' in the Soviet Union,
``nothing, nothing, nothing,'' he said when telling of the scrutiny
customs officials gave an illustrated biography he was carrying for
his sister.
   Broue, the French historian, found Alexandra through a new Moscow
group called Memorial that is compiling an archive on Stalin's
millions of victims and hopes to erect monuments to them, Volkow
said.
   ``Alexandra had taken the decision to emerge from her anonymity,
to publicly acknowledge her relation and her heritage, only a few
weeks earlier,'' he said.
   Her brother said Alexandra, who had lost her parents and been
reviled, jailed and sent to internal exile because of her name, told
him ``she wasn't afraid of anything any longer. Not after all that
had happened to her, and her illness.''
   ``I hope she survives,'' he said. ``I want my daughters to know
their aunt.''
   He met with members of Memorial and thanked them for finding his
only sister. Volkow said he was surprised and gratified to find
Trotsky and members of his family prominently featured in a mural of
Stalin's victims in the group's office.
   Most of his five days in Moscow was spent with his sister,
speaking through an interpreter, and he discovered that memories of
their parting haunted her as their grandfather's death haunted him.
   ``She told me she remembered perfectly the departure, when I left
with our mother,'' he said. ``She always had a deep existential
doubt. Why? Because our mother left with me, not with her.''
   He said Broue found the answer to that riddle of the day
Trotsky's daughter Zina abandoned one of her two children. ``When
Stalin expelled my mother, he allowed her to take only her youngest
child,'' Volkow said.
   Alexandra, left with her paternal grandmother, eventually spent
six months in jail and five years in internal exile. She returned to
Moscow in 1954, after Stalin died, to study engineering, marry, bear
a daughter and live in fearful anonymity.
   Her brother, also an engineer, went to live with Trotsky after
their mother committed suicide in Paris. His father, Platon Volkow,
and Alexandra's, Zahar Mobline, died in Stalin's camps along with
other members of the family.
   Volkow considers himself a Mexican and found the Soviet Union to
be ``like another planet.''
   ``The truth is that the country is really alien to me,'' he said.
``I left so young I have practically no memories, no memories. Maybe
just the beginning of winter, the cold. ''
   A visit to the house in Moscow where his family had lived stirred
little but a childhood recollection of cold light pouring through
huge windows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
