<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     01-29 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto's Main Rival Wins Assembly Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key rival of Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto won a seat in the National Assembly, election results
indicated Sunday, and he is expected to lead opposition forces in
the legislature.
   The official returns from the by-election Saturday gave Ghulam
Mustafi Jatoi's conservative Islamic Democratic Alliance seven seats
in the assembly and Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning People's Party four
seats.
   The victory for Jatoi and his party came after a humiliating
defeat in his home district of southern Sind Province in an election
in November.
   Two other seats went to an independent and the candidate of a
minor party.
   Lawmakers from Ms. Bhutto's party and its allies still outnumber
the nine-party Moslem alliance by two-to-one in the assembly, or
lower house Parliament.
   Sunday's results were not considered a defeat for Ms. Bhutto
because all the Moslem alliance's victories remained confined to the
wealthy and populous Punjab province, where it emerged strongest in
November when Pakistan held its first free elections in 11 years.
   The returns published by the Pakistan Election Commission on
Sunday indicated that just under 50 percent of the 3 million
eligible voters turned out for the by-election, the same percentage
as voted in November.
   At stake were 13 seats in the 237-seat National Assembly and
seven seats in provincial assemblies of districts where candidates
in November won more than one seat, or where the vote was postponed
because a candidate died.
   In the provincial contests, the two leading parties won three
seats each, and an independent won one.
   Chief Election Commissioner S.A. Nusrat said voting was calm and
peaceful except for in one district of Lahore, the Punjab capital,
where police had to break up a stone-throwing melee between rival
supporters of Ms. Bhutto and Jatoi. Nusrat said the disturbance did
not disrupt voting.
   Sunday's results reflected November's voting pattern.
   Ms. Bhutto's party emerged the strongest nationwide but fell
short of an outright majority. The Moslem alliance, which includes
proteges of the late military dictator Mohammad Zia ul-Haq,
established a power base in Punjab where it now controls the
provincial legislature.
   Zia died in a plane crash in August, clearing the way for Ms.
Bhutto and her allies to assume power. Zia overthrew Ms. Bhutto's
father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a bloodless 1977 coup
and ordered him hanged two years later on conviction of conspiring
to murder a political opponent.
   Jatoi was a minister in Ms. Bhutto's Cabinet and was jailed for
15 months for his opposition to Zia's rule.
   He remained with the Pakistan People's Party until Ms. Bhutto
returned home from self-imposed exile in Europe in 1986 to head the
party.
   Jatoi opposed Ms. Bhutto's leadership and the governing of a
Moslem nation by a woman. He broke away from the party to form his
National People's Party.
   When the new members of the National Assembly take their seats,
Jatoi is expected to be the floor leader for the Islamic Democratic
Alliance forces.
</TEXT>
