<FIRST>r a AM-Commodities-PACs     01-29 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities-PACs,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traders Donate Heavily To Political Campaigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political action committees affiliated with
Chicago futures markets have donated millions of dollars to the
election campaigns of officials who oversee regulation of the
exchanges, which are now targets of a federal investigation, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   The Auction Markets Political Action Committee, which represents
the Chicago Board of Trade, and the Commodity Futures Political
Fund, representing the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, have funded the
campaigns of lawmakers on congressional committees regulating
futures markets, the Chicago Tribune said.
   The two exchanges are being investigated by federal officials who
suspect widespread fraud in trading practices.
   Authorities refuse to comment, but the investigation reportedly
centers on allegations that as many as 100 brokers and traders
systematically cheated customers in illegal trades.
   Some commodities experts say the investigation could bring about
new government regulations, which traders oppose.
   ``The worst result would be that it would cast a shadow over the
entire industry, ... and we wind up facing regulatory proposals,''
said Alan J. Brody, president of New York's Commodity Exchange.
   The Tribune reported that traders donated $1.4 million to the two
PACs linked to the Chicago markets during the 1987-88 election cycle.
   Of that amount, $856,750 was donated to congressional campaigns _
up sharply from the $535,100 the PACs donated in the 1985-86 cycle,
the newspaper said.
   The contributions included some hefty gifts to lawmakers who have
introduced bills that would benefit the commodities industries, the
Tribune said.
   In 1984, the two groups gave $21,000 to Campaign America, a PAC
set up by Sen. Robert Dole, R-Kan. Individual traders also donated
$49,500 to Dole's PAC, the Tribune said.
   Dole, then chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, helped to
work out a special tax bailout to save traders about $300 million
annually, the paper reported.
   Dole spokesman Walt Riker, reached Sunday at his Springfield,
Va., home, denied the senator had been influenced by the donations.
   ``PAC contributions have absolutely no relation to how a member
votes, and to say otherwise is garbage,'' Riker said. ``At least
speaking for Senator Dole, I know that that's true.''
   Rep. Martin Russo, D-Ill., received $38,850 from the two PACS and
other sources related to the commodities industry in the 1981-82
election cycle, and an additional $25,000 in 1983-84, the newspaper
said.
   In 1981, Russo sponsored a measure that would have closed a tax
loophole for everyone except traders, leaving them with a savings of
as much as $400 million annually, according to Common Cause, a
citizens' interest group in Washington.
   The bill did not pass, and Russo has denied he was influenced by
the contributions. He has not been accused of any illegality, the
newspaper said.
   In 1984, the PACs contributed $20,000 to the re-election campaign
of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who was then head of the Senate
Agriculture Committee, which is one of the panels that oversees the
commodities industry, the newspaper said.
   Calls to the congressional offices and residences of Russo and
Helms were not answered Sunday.
</TEXT>
