<FIRST>r w AM-Budget-Taxes     01-29 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Taxes,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Staff Chief Admonishes Congress To Negotiate In Good
Faith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu declared
Sunday that ``positioning ... to deal with eventual failure'' by
some members of Congress could wreck efforts to reach a bipartisan
budget agreement.
   ``If that's the additude going in, then none of us will
succeed,'' Sununu said in a broadcast interview.
   Sununu also said a proposal for a fee on deposits to help shore
up ailing savings and loans remains a live option, despite
widespread congressional and industry opposition to the plan.
   ``There are a variety of options being examined,'' Sununu said on
ABC's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   He said opponents of the proposed fee were able to ``take the
lead and put the worst foot forward on the plan'' after the Bush
administration made a good-faith effort at early consulations with
House and Senate leaders.
   ``I guess the most disappointing part of the whole thing is the
effort that was being made to get the Congress early enough to let
them be apart of crafting alternatives resulted in a firestorm on
one alternative that was not necessarily the leading candidate,''
Sununu said.
   The savings and loan proposal would call for a fee of about $2.50
for every $1,000 deposited in federally insured savings and loans
and commercial banks.
   Disclosure that the Treasury Department was considering such a
plan complicated Bush's otherwise harmonious first week in office.
   While repeating Bush's assertion Friday that the plan had not yet
reached the White House, Sununu noted that financial institutions
have long paid a fee for federal deposit insurance.
   He said the plan under study was simply a matter of ``taking the
current fee and adjusting it to affect the reality.''
   If financial institutions were to pass along such an increased
fee directly to depositers, American savers still would be getting a
bargain for having their savings insured by their government, he
said.
   Sununu said Bush still intends to work with Congress on forging
bipartisan solutions on both the savings and loan and the larger
budget crises.
   ``We're looking for the Democrat Congress to be part of
developing a solution,'' he said. ``And any concern we have is ...
the different slices of Congress positioning itself to deal with
evenutal failure.''
   Interviewed on the same program, Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
and Rep. William Gray III, D-Pa., both voiced skepticism over Bush's
announced intention to produce a budget by Feb. 9 that meets
deficit-reduction targets without new taxes.
   Hollings, charirman of the Senate Commerce Committee, said the
administration was glossing over the deficit problem with
too-optimistic economic assumptions.
   And Gray said the president had put himself ``in a box'' with his
no-new-taxes pledge, but should relent and vow support of between
$13 billion and $14 billion in new revenues.
   Gray is immediate past chairman of the House Budget Committee, a
rotating assignment, and a member of the House Democratic leadership.
   Sununu, asked about the remarks of Hollings and Gray, said:
``Both the senator and the congressman appeared to be positioning in
case there's a failure. This adminstration ... is committed to
moving to a success.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Tex., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, also voiced skepticism about the no-new-taxes pledge in
an interview on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
   ``I think the odds are against him on that one,'' Bentsen said
when asked about Bush's chances of bringing the budget deficit down
to $100 billion without raising taxes.
   Bentsen also criticized the proposed fee on savings deposits,
saying ``that trial balloon of putting a tax on deposits was really
very foolish.''
</TEXT>
