<HEAD>President Nursing Cold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush cancelled a planned visit to the
presidential retreat at Camp David on Sunday and stayed home at the
White House to nurse a persistent cold.
   Bush, whose first full week in office was marked by long working
hours and frequent short trips about town, decided to take it easy
in hopes of conquering the cold that by week's end had left his
voice noticeably raspy, according to aides.
   ``He just has a cold, a regular cold,and is taking some
decongestants,'' said spokesman Bruce Zanca.
   Bush had planned to travel by helicopter to Camp David in the
nearby mountains of Maryland and spend most of the day there. He had
invited House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and his wife to join him
there for what White House aides said was to have been a purely
social gettogether.
   Bush's hoarseness was evident Friday at his first news conference
as president. ``I sound worse than I feel,'' he said.
