<FIRST>r a AM-TravelBuddy     01-29 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Travel Buddy,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Matching Travelers Puts Pair on the Road</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dona in 2nd graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers who don't want to see the sights
alone can find a friend through Travel Buddy, which provides
companions who will accompany ``anyone, any age, to anywhere in the
world.''
   Since Dona M. Risdall began operating Travel Buddy out of her
home in suburban Bloomington in 1987, the service has provided
``buddies'' for more than 100 travelers in the United States and
overseas. The buddies, who are carefully screened, get their tickets
paid by the clients, but pay other expenses.
   ``I think they relax a lot more when they're on a trip with a
buddy. I think it's extra security,'' Ms. Risdall said. ``I call it
`Travel Buddy' because that's what they are _ a really good buddy to
the client.''
   Among Ms. Risdall's clients are the elderly, the slightly
handicapped and small children. The youngest were a couple of girls,
ages 6 and 7, who flew with a buddy to visit their father in Texas.
   ``There's a lot of early retirees that have the money but have no
one to go with,'' Ms. Risdall said.
   She got the idea for the service at her job as a front-desk
assistant at an athletic club in Bloomington.
   ``Just time and time again I heard so many say, `My wife or
husband has passed away,' and they'd love to travel, but they don't
want to go alone,'' she said.
   Ms. Risdall, 49, started her business with about $5,000, which
was used mostly for printing and mailing brochures.
   For a fee _ $65 for non-members, $45 for members _ Risdall lines
up a traveler with a buddy of similar background and interests. The
annual membership fee is $25, and travelers either can make their
own travel arrangements or Ms. Risdall will make them through a
travel agent she works with.
   Ms. Risdall screens all prospective buddies and requires
references. She said she has about 50 men and women of all ages in
her listings.
   This month Ms. Risdall began a branch operation in Dallas out of
a former Buddy's home, and she's thinking about a similar branch in
Arizona.
   There are other organizations that provide companions for
disabled travelers, said Peter Shaw-Lawrence, of the New York
City-based Society for the Advancement of Travel for the Handicapped.
   ``Each of these organizations may have slightly different
things,'' he said.
   A get-acquainted session is arranged between the traveler and the
prospective buddy if both are from around Minneapolis. If the client
lives out of state, Ms. Risdall chooses the buddy.
   Agatha Drilling, 70, of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, contacted Travel
Buddy after reading a magazine article about the service. She was
lined up with a companion who drove with her to Phoenix in December.
   ``I think it's great,'' said Ms. Drilling, who plans to use the
service again. ``You get somebody who you can feel is trustworthy
because they were checked out.''
   Her ``buddy,'' Natalie Kirstiuk, 40, of Fridley, said she applied
to be a buddy because she loves to travel.
   ``It was a chance to see more of the country that I haven't
seen,'' she said.
   Ms. Risdall has provided buddies for travelers going to Europe
and Australia, but the trip can be as short as to North Dakota.
   Ms. Risdall, whose friends tease her for being a workaholic,
hasn't taken a vacation herself for years. ``When a trip to Hawaii
comes along, I'm going to go,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
