<FIRST>r a AM-DestroyerRefloated     01-29 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Destroyer Refloated,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>USS Spruance Refloated After Three Days Aground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy salvage teams managed to refloat the
destroyer USS Spruance after the ship had been aground for three
days near a Bahamian Island, Navy officials said Sunday.
   The ship based in Mayport ran aground Wednesday off Andros
Island, 150 miles southeast of Miami, during a routine training
operation.
   It took the combination of two successive high tides and the
steady tugging of two other ships to free the destroyer, said Lt.
Cmdr. Tim Taylor of the Mayport Naval Station.
   ``The USS Grasp was really the main player in this drama,''
Taylor said. The salvage ship and the USNS Mohawk, an ocean-going
tug, pulled the 563-foot Spruance free shortly before midnight
Saturday.
   Navy divers inspected Spruance's hull Sunday. ``They confirmed
the hull is intact,'' Taylor said.
   But he added that the propellers had been damaged so the Grasp is
towing the disabled destroyer to a shipyard in Pascagoula, Miss.,
for repairs.
   The Navy was still investigating the cause of the grounding,
Taylor said. Damage estimates won't be available until the destroyer
reaches Pascagoula.
   No one was injured and the Spruance's crew remained aboard the
vessel.
</TEXT>
