<FIRST>r a AM-ChessQuarterfinals     01-29 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess Quarterfinals,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Soviet Chess Champ Karpov In Draw With Icelander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarterfinal contest for the World Chess
Championship Candidates series resumes Monday after a first-match
draw between former world champion Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet
Union and Iceland's Johann Hjartarson.
   The winner of the Candidates series of matches will challenge
world champion Garri Kasparov for his world title in 1990.
   Hjartarson, 25, playing white, offered the draw after 15 moves
Saturday and Karpov, 37, accepted.
   The match is only six games, and Karpov must be cautious in
settling for a draw because just one win by Hjartarson would put the
Icelandic grandmaster in a very strong position, one chess analyst
said.
   Chess analysts said the key to Saturday's game, described as the
doubly delayed exchange variation of the Ruy Lopez, was Hjartarson's
11th move, when he moved his Knight to Queen-Bishop 4, positionally
making continuation of the game questionable.
   One analyst said Hjartarson played not so much to win, but to
keep from losing to the 11-time world champion.
   Three quarterfinals matches are under way or about to begin. The
fourth was won by British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman, who
advanced to the semifinals.
</TEXT>
