<FIRST>r a AM-CorrectionsSlaying     01-29 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corrections Slaying,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Search For Answers In Wake Of Correction Chief's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No arrests have been made but revenge is a
strong candidate as motive in the killing nearly two weeks ago of
the head of Oregon's prison system, a man who had received death
threats.
   Michael Francke, 42, formerly a law enforcement official in New
Mexico, was stabbed in the heart the evening of Jan. 17 during an
attack in a parking lot outside the Corrections Department office.
   Police won't divulge many details about the crime, such as any
injuries Francke may have suffered besides the fatal stab wound.
   ``You need to have something that only you know and the murderer
knows, to use for corroboration,'' said Marion County District
Attorney Dale Penn, who's leading the investigation.
   According to published reports, Francke apparently stumbled 25
yards from the parking lot to the building, where he broke a glass
pane in a door before collapsing.
   Late-working colleagues searched for Francke after finding his
car, one door ajar, in the parking lot.
   A guard found his body was found at the rarely used entry. No
weapon was found.
   Robbery hasn't been ruled out as a motive, but Penn said
investigators are pursuing the possibility that Francke's death was
a revenge killing.
   Francke served as a prosecutor, judge and head of corrections in
New Mexico before being hired in May 1987 to take charge of Oregon's
severely overcrowded prison system.
   He no doubt made enemies in both states, investigators have said.
   ``This could be random street violence, a regular old strong-arm
robbery,'' Penn said. ``But it also could be a complicated
conspiracy because of the positions that he has held in the two
states.
   ``It is a very difficult case, just because of his background.''
   Former state Rep. Chuck Sides, a friend of Francke's, said the
corrections chief had shown him a letter threatening his life last
fall. He said he could remember no details of the letter, which
Francke had shrugged off.
   Sides said Francke had told him he was glad to have left the New
Mexico Correction Department because of death threats there.
   But Sides also Francke made comments about death by stabbing
several weeks ago.
   ``I can't remember what brought it up, but he told me exactly how
a person would die with a stab through the heart,'' Sides said.
``Basically, he showed me with his own hand how you would do that.''
   Francke's brother, Patrick Francke Jr., said he doesn't believe
robbery was a motive.
   In an interview from his home in Kansas City, Mo., Patrick
Francke said police appear to have recovered all his brother's
personal effects, including a wallet, credit cards and car keys.
   He also said he can't understand why a robber would single out
his brother, who was 6-foot-3 and weighed more than 200 pounds, as a
target.
   Penn said he can understand the brother's point of view but
insisted that robbery is still a viable motive.
   The district attorney last week gave out a sketchy description of
a man who is believed to have stabbed Francke. Penn said the man had
dark hair and was wearing dark pants and a light coat.
   At the same time, the district attorney said police aren't
getting close to making an arrest in the case.
   ``It was a quick event and the person escaped,'' he said. ``You
generally need to get a break in this kind of case, a tip from the
public or somebody talking.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
