<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Fatal Attraction'' star Glenn Close
says she had to change her appearance because of the recognition she
received after her performance in the film as Alex, the enraged
jilted lover.
   ``I was surprised the picture became the phenomenon it did,''
Close said of the film in a recent interview in the Sunday
Tennessean. ``It was amazing.
   ``I even cut my hair because people were jumping out of my way.
My hair stylist says people come in wanting their hair `done like
Glenn Close's.''' Her blond hair was in a distinctive curly style
for the film.
   ``I am kind of an average-looking woman and, until recently, I've
been able to travel around pretty much without hindrance. Alex has
changed all that, too.
   ``I don't think any of us realized how emotional people would be
about `Fatal Attraction' and how much they'd hate my guts and want
to see me blown away.
   ``I was very upset when I heard that people applauded when the
faithful wife said, `If you come near my family, I'll kill you,' To
me, as I knew the Alex character, she was extremely tragic. All that
was taken away in the final version.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil Diamond concerts scheduled this
week at the Palace of Auburn Hills have lost some of their luster
for some security personnel and some fans, especially those in the
high-priced seats.
   A memorandum warning the holders of the 180 luxury private boxes
or suites in the arena they ``need to close all (rear) draperies,
turn off all lights and TV's and remain seated in their terraces
throughout the concert,'' was issued last week by Thomas Trzos,
director of facility administration. It was sent at Diamond's
request.
   Those suites, many with televisions for sports fans to take in
their instant replays, go for $30,000 to $120,000 a year. But the
occupants could be ejected if they violate Diamond's requests, the
memo said.
   The memo also said the doors would not open until about 6:45 p.m.
because Diamond has demanded that no employees, suiteholders or fans
be allowed to peek into the arena during preparation for the
elaborate show. Concerts start at 8 p.m.
   Sherrie Levy, Diamond's publicist, said his requests may have
been taken out of context.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwin Meese III, the former controversial
attorney general, has found sanctuary of sorts in his new role as a
visiting scholar with the Hoover Institution.
   Meese praised the social policies of the Reagan administration
and championed the cause of public service in a speech on Saturday.
   ``Lest any of you are confused by stereotypes in the news media,
it will be the 1990s we're talking about, not the 1980s,'' Meese
said, sidestepping the potential for discussion of his embattled
tenure in the Reagan administration. He spoke to a crowd of about
400 attending an ``Issues in the '90s'' conference.
   During a break, Meese said he will spend his two-year, part-time
stint as a ``distinguished visiting scholar'' at the conservative
think tank by focusing on Reagan.
   Meese resigned as attorney general last March, following an
investigation into whether he used his political influence for
personal gain. Special prosecutor James C. McKay concluded that
Meese probably had violated federal conflict-of-interest and tax
laws, but he decided not to prosecute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John le Carre's next book isn't expected in
bookstores until June, but fans are already wondering whether the
new Soviet spirit of glasnost will bring the acclaimed spy novelist
in from the cold.
   The question is tantalizing enough to have made the front page of
the respected Sunday Telegraph, which asked: ``If the creator of
(British spycatcher George) Smiley and of Karla, the Soviet
spymaster, has had to come in from the Cold War, what front will he
fight on?''
   Novels like ``Smiley's People'' and the ``The Spy Who Came in
From the Cold,'' whose undercover skullduggery is set in the
pre-Mikhail Gorbachev era, have made le Carre a master of the genre.
   His upcoming latest novel, ``The Russia House,'' is described in
his publisher's catalog as ``a spy story and an anti-spy story, a
story of Cold Warriors who continue to dance in their gray cellars
after the music has ended,'' The Sunday Telegraph reported.
