<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-USFilmFestival     01-29 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Film Festival,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moon Shot Documentary Leads Award Winners At United States Film Festival</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lower-case ``sex, lies and videotape'' is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``For All Mankind,'' a documentary
composed entirely of film shot by the Apollo astronauts who went to
the moon from 1968 to 1972, was the big winner at this year's United
States Film Festival.
   The movie captured both the Audience Award and the Grand Jury
Prize as best documentary Saturday at the 11th annual festival held
in Park City Jan. 20 through Sunday. The festival fosters
independent films.
   Producer-director Al Reinert finished the film just one week ago,
the same day it had its first screening at the event, sponsored by
Robert Redford's Sundance Institute and the Utah Film Development
Office.
   ``I'm a writer,'' Reinert said after receiving the two awards.
``I just wandered into filmmaking 10 years ago. I was just amazed no
one made this film 10 years before that. I always thought going to
the moon was our highest pyramid. This is the most extraordinary
stuff ever shot by human beings.''
   Reinert received $5,000 for winning the Grand Jury Prize, as did
director Nancy Savoca, whose film ``True Love'' captured the same
prize in the dramatic category.
   ``True Love,'' set in an Italian-American neighborhood of New
York City's borough of the Bronx, tells the story of a young
couple's final weeks preparing for marriage and their relationships
with family and friends.
   A new category at this year's festival was the Filmmaker's
Trophy, given to the best films as voted by the competition's
filmmakers themselves.
   The filmmakers' choice for best documentary was ``John Huston.''
Narrated by actor Robert Mitchum, the movie by Frank Martin and Joni
Levin followed the life and career of the late director who made
such films as ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``The Dead,'' ``The Treasure
of the Sierre Madre,'' and ``The Man Who Would Be King.''
   The Audience Award in the dramatic category went to ``sex, lies
and videotape,'' which also received its first screening at the
festival.
   A psychological drama by first-time director Steven Soderbergh,
the film revolves around the soured relationship of a married
couple, which Soderbergh patterned after a relationship of his own.
   ``I thought our audience was going to be very small. It is so
personal that I didn't think anyone would relate to it,'' he said.
   Winner of the Filmmakers' dramatic Award was ``Powwow Highway,''
a comedy-drama about two young Northern Cheyenne Indians who take a
journey of self-discovery across uhe American plains. It was
directed by Jonathan Wacks.
</TEXT>
