<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs     01-29 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Hangs 22 More Drug Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran hanged 22 drug smugglers in the past
three days, raising to 130 the number of people executed in an
anti-narcotics crackdown this month, Tehran Radio reported Sunday.
   Smugglers are hanged in public in the early hours. Their bodies
are left hanging to emphasize to morning rush-hour crowds the
government's determination to stamp out drug addiction.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said seven smugglers were
hanged in northeastern Khorasan province, six in the capital,
Tehran, and the rest in cities throughout the country.
   Those hanged in Khorasan were Afghan citizens found with 163
pounds of opium and 8.8 pounds of heroin, the radio said.
   The Afghans also were charged with illegal entry into Iran,
possessing weapons and resisting arrest in a shootout with
government agents. The radio did not say if there were any
casualties in the clash.
   Officials seized more than 33,000 pounds of opium, 213 pounds of
heroin, and 22 pounds of morphine from the other smugglers, it said.
   The executions began two weeks ago after a new law mandated death
for anyone found in possession of even small amounts of narcotics,
or found guilty of causing widespread drug addiction.
   Hangings will be suspended for 10 days from Feb. 1 during
celebrations marking the anniversary of the Islamic Revolution that
toppled the Iranian monarchy in 1979, the government has announced.
   About 1,500 people have been arrested in the crackdown.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia, said
1 million of Iran's 50 million people are believed to abuse drugs.
   It said the price of heroin has risen dramatically since the
start of the crackdown, but it did not give prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
