<SECOND>AM-BRF--Angry Elephants,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Elephants Terrorize Village In Search Of Missing Calf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty angry elephants invaded a remote
forest village twice last week and destroyed several huts while
searching for a missing elephant calf, United News of India reported
Sunday.
   The calf had fallen into a 23-foot-deep well when the herd was
being chased by Forest Department workers in the Salboni forest, 70
miles west of Calcutta, the news agency said. The workers were
trying to shoo away the herd that had arrived in the area two months
ago, damaging crops and frightening villagers.
   The elephant calf was trapped in the well for 24 hours while
villagers prevented forest workers from rescuing it, UNI said.
   In the meantime, the elephant herd thundered into the village in
search of the calf, UNI said. No one was injured during the
elephants' two forays, but residents fled from their houses, the
news agency said.
   The villagers subsequently permitted Forest Department workers to
rescue the calf. The elephants resisted further attempts to chase
them out of the region. UNI's report from the remote area did not
give the village's name.
</TEXT>
