<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MunitionsPlant     01-29 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Munitions Plant,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of Closed Plant Objects To Army Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a bankrupt munitions company
says an Army recommendation to detonate some of the plant's
explosives on the spot rather than risk moving them is unnecessary
because there is no danger of an accidental blast.
   Lakeland residents have nothing to fear, said Edward Geoghegan,
who was chief executive officer when Sooner Defense of Florida Inc.
filed for protection from its creditors July 19. The company is
being liquidated by a federal bankruptcy court.
   ``I know one thing, I'd be willing to take myself and my family
out there and I'll go look in the buildings,'' he said Friday. ``The
only thing I cannot speak to is what the government has done since
they've been out there.''
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Thomas Baynes, who is presiding over
the Sooner proceedings, had asked the government to remove any
hazardous materials from the plant, which made fuses to detonate
other explosives for the military.
   An Army explosives expert, Capt. Kurt Ponting, inspected the site
and testified Wednesday that one or two small buildings at the plant
a few miles west of Lakeland should be blown up. He said he will
head a special team to decide which explosives can be moved and
which should be detonated.
   Ponting's principal concern was over a compound called lead
azide, described in chemical textbooks as a severe explosion risk.
It was usually placed for an hour or two in drying ovens about the
size of outhouses, but some has been in a couple of ovens ever since
the plant closed, officials said.
   ``Certainly there are dangerous explosives out there, there's no
doubt about that,'' Geoghegan conceded. But he added: ``I would
match Sooner's handling of explosives against any ammunition company
in the whole country. We were the best.''
   Until the hearing, even government attorneys had been saying it
would be a relatively simple and short process to remove the
explosives, said Robert Soriano, attorney for Citizens Fidelity Bank
and Trust of Louisville, Ky., Sooner's largest secured creditor.
   Told of the Army proposal, Don Seeger, a former Sooner explosives
expert, said, ``I'd have to see it, but it sounds like a drastic
move to blow the material in place when it's only been in storage
six months.''
   Trustee Daniel Bakst, who was appointed by Baynes in December to
liquidate the company, said: ``I agree with Geoghegan that it's
blown out of proportion.''
   Ponting estimates it will cost the government up to $1 million
and take up to four months to remove all explosives.
</TEXT>
