<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Iraq     01-29 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Iraq,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Agrees To Joint Military Committee With Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein agreed Sunday to a
U.N. proposal to set up a joint military committee with Iran,
Baghdad Radio said.
   Diplomats in the Iraqi capital said it is a significant
breakthrough in U.N. efforts to revive stalled peace talks to end
the eight-year gulf war.
   The radio did not elaborate on the committee's function.
   But the diplomats, who requested anonymity, said a joint military
group signaled hopes of a troop withdrawal by both sides. The group
could work with U.N. military observers monitoring the Aug. 20
cease-fire, they said.
   Iraq's and Iran's failure to agree on a withdrawal, called for
under a July 1987 Security Council resolution, has been a major
sticking point in talks that have dragged on inconclusively for five
months.
   State-owned Baghdad Radio said Saddam agreed to the joint
committee during a four-hour meeting Sunday with Jan Eliasson,
special envoy of U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Eliasson, Sweden's ambassador to the United Nations, arrived in
Baghdad Friday after four days of talks with Iranian leaders in
Tehran.
   Iraq's broadcast said Saddam also agreed to lift a ban barring
Iranian-bound civilian flights from flying over Iraq.
   The radio did not elaborate. But Saddam appears to be making an
effort to give new impetus to the stalled negotiations.
   Talks broke down in Geneva on Nov. 11. Iran says it considers
further talks futile unless Iraq halts what it calls delaying
tactics.
   Baghdad Radio reported that Saddam reiterated to Eliasson that
Iraq rejects any Iranian preconditions to resuming negotiations.
   Iran says that before it returns to the negotiating table, Iraq
must agree to the complete and immediate implementation of the
Security Council resolution, including withdrawing troops to the
prewar border.
   Baghdad Radio said Saddam agreed to participate in the joint
military committee and to lift the flight ban ``out of Iraq's
keenness for the U.N. envoy's mission to succeed and its readiness
to cooperate with him.''
   Saddam called on Iran to display the same commitment to the
United Nations resolution ``through practical steps and deeds,'' the
radio reported.
   A spokesman for the U.N. mission, Gianni Picco, declined comment
on Sunday's developments.
   Iran charges Iraq is blocking agreement by refusing to withdraw
from 260 square miles of Iranian border territory captured in final
stages of the fighting. Iraq says it will not withdraw until Iran
agrees to surrender its right to search ships in the gulf for
Iraq-bound war materiel.
   The two sides also dispute ownership of the Shatt-Al-Arab
waterway, their prewar southern boundary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
