<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya 1stLd-Writethru   01-29 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0672,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says West Germany to Increase Penalties for Illegal Exports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout To UPDATE with report that nuclear materials originating
in the United States shipped through a West German company in 1984. No
pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government, under fire for its
handling of the Libyan scandal, will impose much harsher penalties
for illegal exports of materials that could be used to make chemical
weapons, a newspaper said Sunday.
   Also Sunday, a magazine reported that nuclear materials that
originated in the United States were sent to India through a West
German company in 1984, and suggested they could have been used to
make atomic weapons.
   West German authorities are investigating several companies
linked to shipments for a Libyan plant that U.S. officials say was
designed to make chemical weapons. Libyan officials say the plant
will make pharmaceuticals.
   Some U.S. congressmen say West German officials looked the other
way while German companies made possibly illegal exports to Libya
and other countries.
   The West German government says it plans to stiffen export
controls to hinder shipment of material that could be used for
chemical and atomic weapons.
   The newspaper, Welt am Sonntag, released what it said were
details of those plans, saying they are contained in a ``secret
paper'' the government will present to Parliament. It did not say
when.
   According to the newspaper, the government wants to double the
maximum fine for such violations from $273,000 to $546,000 and to
increase the maximum jail sentence from three years to five.
   A key part of the proposal would be changing current law to allow
seizure of any profits made from illegal sales, the newspaper said.
   The West German inquiries also center on allegations that German
companies helped Iraq with its chemical weapons program and on
suspicions that sensitive nuclear materials were delivered to
Pakistan.
   Iraq has acknowledged using chemical weapons during its war with
Iran, and reports say Pakistan has the ability to make nuclear
weapons.
   West German leaders have denied U.S. allegations they were too
slow in launching investigations against suspected violators of
export laws. Meanwhile, more allegations are cropping up weeks after
the Libyan scandal first broke.
   In editions to appear Monday, Der Spiegel magazine said the West
German company Degussa sent 210 pounds of beryllium to India in 1984
and that a ``large part of this material originated in the U.S.A.''
   Der Spiegel said it based its report on unidentified documents to
which the magazine had obtained access.
   Beryllium frequently is used in nuclear reactors. Der Spiegel
said it can also be used in the production of atomic weapons.
   The magazine said Degussa served as middleman in the shipment.
The news magazine did not identify the American parties allegedly
involved.
   ``The transaction occurred at a time when there were worldwide
rumors that India was developing an atomic bomb,'' the magazine said.
   According to Der Spiegel, the material was sent to the Bhabha
Atomic Research Center near Bombay.
   The magazine said West German authorities approved the permits
because the government did not believe the exports would help India
build nuclear weapons.
   Neither government nor Degussa officials could be reached for
comment Sunday night.
   In a separate article, the magazine said West German intelligence
officials knew ``for a long time'' of German shipments to Iraq of
chemicals that could be used to make biological weapons.
   But according to the magazine, the intelligence officials did not
inform the West German chancellor's office of what it knew ``until
the worldwide uproar over German shipments to Libya.''
   West German officials have not acknowledged involvement by German
companies in a possible biological arms plant in Iraq.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
