<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Taba 1stLd-Writethru a0698 01-29 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Taba, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Agrees To Let Egyptian Flag Fly Over Taba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with Egypt property compensation
to Israelis; picks up 5th pvs: The talks...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel agreed on Sunday to let Egypt raise its
flag over the disputed Taba border area in a symbolic concession
reflecting Israel's plans to return the 250-acre beach strip to
Egyptian rule.
   Israel acceded to Egypt's request to fly its flag in an attempt
to get talks moving on the last obstacles before the land along the
Red Sea is handed back, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel.
   ``We hope this decision will help defuse the tensions that have
been created in the past few days and enable the working committees
to resume their talks,'' Liel said.
   He said Egypt's ambassador to Israel, Mohammed Bassiouny, was
pleased by Israel's response.
   Late Sunday, Egypt issued a presidential decree authorizing its
Tourism Ministry to negotiate compensation for Israeli property
owners in Taba, Israel radio said. Israeli officials termed the
document ``moderate'' and said they will study it, the radio
reported.
   The talks over Taba ran into trouble last week when Egyptian
officials said they would consider the land to be under Egypt's
sovereignty as of Sunday, 60 days after an international arbitration
panel sided with Egypt.
   The declaration alarmed Israeli officials, who first want to
settle issues such as access for Israeli tourists and compensation
for Israeli owners of a luxury hotel and a holiday resort village in
Taba.
   The beach strip, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war,
has been a subject of dispute between the countries since 1982. At
that time, Israel refused to return it to Egypt along with the rest
of the Sinai Peninsula under the terms of the nations' 1979 peace
treaty.
   In 1986, the two sides agreed to take the dispute to an
international arbitration panel in Geneva for a binding ruling. The
panel drew a border that put Taba in Egyptian territory.
   Liel said Egypt is to raise its flag on its side of the border
marker, about 150 yards from the Gulf of Aqaba, and Israel is to do
the same on its side.
</TEXT>
