<FIRST>r i AM-RichardLeakey     01-29 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Richard Leakey,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Anthropolgist May Rejoin Kenya Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthropologist Richard Leakey said on
Sunday he has been asked to return as director of the National
Museums of Kenya, a post he resigned a week ago.
   But he said he will await a formal offer from the board of
trustees before he agrees to return. ``Until then I'll stay in my
shamba (farm),'' he said.
   Leakey resigned on Jan. 20 to ``facilitate the reorganization
currently being carried out by the Ministry of Home Affairs,'' he
said at the time.
   The 45-year-old son anthropologist said in a press release that
the ministry had appointed a new board of trustees for the museum _
which houses Africa's best collection of fossils and human artifacts
_ without consulting him.
   He said Sunday that the situation is confusing and that he was
waiting for the government to dissolve the new board and reinstate
the previous one.
   ``There can't be two boards,'' Leakey said. ``The ministry did
not say the board it had appointed had been dissolved. But the old
board had not been legally dissolved either.''
   Last month, a Nairobi newspaper, The Standard, quoted unnamed
museum employees as blaming Leakey for an exodus of African
scientists from the institution, which has a staff of 300. But
museum employees later signed a public letter defending their
director.
   A Kenya citizen, Leakey is a high school dropout who learned
anthropolgy from two pioneers: his parents, Louis and Mary. He had
headed the museum for 20 years.
   In 1972, Leakey found a skull of a man-like creature while
leading an expedition near Lake Turkana in northwestern Kenya.
   The skull was later established to be at least 2.5 million years
old, pushing mankind's prehistoric family tree back at least a
million years.
   Until Richard's 1972 discovery, the oldest precusor of man was
thought to date back 1.5 million years, based on discoveries made by
his father 14 years earlier.
</TEXT>
