<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     01-29 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Appeals For Support in Upcoming Talks with Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa appealed to
supporters on Sunday to support his talks with the government that
he said could lead to greater economic and political freedom.
   ``I know there are many opponents, both on our side and on the
other one. I need your help because it is not going to be easy,''
Walesa told 3,000 people at St. Brygida's church in Gdansk.
   Solidarity leaders and top government officials on Friday agreed
to meet Feb. 6 for the first session of broad-based talks between
the authorities and opposition that will decide the future of the
banned union.
   Solidarity leaders have fought to regain the union's legal status
ever since parliament banned it in late 1982 following the December
1981 martial law crackdown.
   ``The whole evil and present dramatic situation had its source in
monopoly, so monopoly will have to be replaced with pluralism,''
Walesa said.
   The word pluralism is used in Poland to refer to greater
political and economic freedom and monopoly refers to the communist
party's control over economic and political activities.
   At a news conference on Saturday, Solidarity adviser Bronislaw
Geremek said that both the government and Solidarity agreed that
reform was necessary to combat Poland's deteriorating economy.
   The Solidarity leader said that the union had no intention of
trying to assume political power.
</TEXT>
