<FIRST>r a AM-JacksonsvilleFire     01-29 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jacksonsville Fire,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Five Businesses In Texas Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke drifted through the downtown
area Sunday as firefighters doused hot spots from a blaze that
roared through a two-story commercial building, destroying five
stores.
   The blaze started Saturday night and spread quickly through the
building's empty second floor and then into the stores below and
another nearby, officials said.
   One firefighter suffered a back injury and the owner of a jewelry
store in the building complained of chest pains when she saw the
fire and was hospitalized.
   An investigation into the cause of the blaze was to begin Monday,
after hot spots in the brick, wood and metal ruin cooled.
   ``There's so much rubble, we'll have to get each hot spot one at
a time,'' said Capt. Joel Moore of the Jacksonville Fire Department.
``With the damage as extensive as it is, it will be difficult to
determine the origin and cause of the fire.''
   The largest business destroyed was the flagship of the 26-store
J.B. White department store chain, which has occupied the
63-year-old building since 1951. Owner John B. White estimated the
store's losses at $250,000 to $300,000. White said he was unsure
whether he would rebuild the store, which was founded by his father
in this town of 13,000 about 90 miles southeast of Dallas.
   Four other retailers, including the jewelry store and two
clothing stores within the building and a tobacco shop next door,
also were destroyed.
   Estimates of losses suffered by the other businesses were not
immediately available.
</TEXT>
