<FIRST>r a AM-RudyRemembers     01-29 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rudy Remembers,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departing Federal Prosecutor Looks Back on Tumltuous Tenure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 5{ years since he became U.S. attorney for
the Southern District of New York, Rudolph W. Giuliani has been
called many things: gangbuster, muckraker, publicity hound and
merciless zealot of law and order.
   In a recent interview with The Associated Press, Giuliani, who
announced Jan. 10 that he would leave his post by the end of the
month, assessed his mistakes and triumphs.
   Giuliani, 44, reiterated that he plans to practice law and decide
during the next two months whether to run for mayor.
   Giuliani, a Republican who abandoned the No. 3 spot in the Reagan
Justice Department in 1983 to head the country's most prominent
federal prosecutor's office, gained attention with his aggressive
campaign against organized crime in New York.
   A public official of Italian descent who was willing to use the
word ``Mafia'' at news conferences, Giuliani became a media darling
as he sent the heads of New York crime families and numerous
Sicilian, Hispanic and Asian drug cartels to prison.
   When he turned the same racketeering laws on insider traders and
political grafters, protests arose on Wall Street and in political
clubhouses, complaining Giuliani was too eager to bring criminal
charges and too willing to announce them at news conferences.
   ``I don't take great delight in prosecuting people or sending
them to prison,'' said Giuliani. ``I haven't made criminal anything
that Congress hasn't made criminal.''
   One mistake Giuliani concedes was the hasty insider trading
indictment of Wall Street executives Robert Freeman, Richard Wigton
and Timothy Tabor. The financial community was outraged in February
1987 when Wigton was led away in handcuffs from his office.
   The charges were dropped three months later when a judge refused
to give prosecutors more time to prepare for trial. Giuliani
promised to re-indict the trio but has yet to do so, prompting
critics to charge he had no case or only a weak one and hoped to
pressure the three men into striking a plea bargain.
   ``The case was considerably more complicated _ for all sorts of
reasons _ than we recognized,'' said Giuliani.
   Some of his harshest criticism came for the unsuccessful
prosecution of former Miss America Bess Myerson, 64.
   Many people wondered why Giuliani made a federal case of
Myerson's alleged bribery of a divorce court judge with a
$19,000-a-year city job for the judge's daughter.
   ``That could be asked of all the federal prosecutions that we
bring,'' said Giuliani, ticking off charges brought against scores
of city electrical inspectors and county highway inspectors for
bribes as small as $500.
   His toughest case? ``Wedtech,'' Giuliani answers without
hesitation, because it involved ``people who were close to my
supervisor, the attorney general of the United States.''
   The investigation of the now-defunct Wedtech Corp., a Bronx
defense contractor, led to the racketeering conviction of former
U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and several others.
   Defense lawyers claimed then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III was
just as heavily involved in the scandal. To defuse the so-called
``Meese defense,'' a prosecutor _ with Giuliani's approval _ told
the jury Meese was a ``sleaze'' but said it had no bearing on the
Biaggi trial.
   ``I believe most people on the outside (of the Justice
Department) agreed with the comment,'' said Giuliani, who declined
to give his personal opinion of Meese, who was never charged with
criminal activities.
   ``There's no doubt that it was a justifiable comment based on the
evidence in that case,'' Giuliani said warily.
</TEXT>
