<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Knudsen     01-29 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Knudsen,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former White House Photographer Dies After Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert LeRoy Knudsen, whose photographs
chronicled nearly three decades of major White House events, has
died at Bethesda Naval Hospital after a heart attack.
   The 61-year-old Knudsen joined the White House photographers'
staff in 1946, being detailed there from the Navy secretary's office
following his graduation from the Naval Photographic School in
Pensacola, Fla.
   Knudsen's photographs include the 1948 and 1952 elections of
Presidents Truman and Eisenhower, the historic 1959 meeting between
Eisenhower and Soviet leader Nikita Krushchev, the autopsy of slain
President Kennedy in 1963, President Nixon's 1972 trips to China and
the Soviet Union, Nixon's 1974 farewell in the wake of the
Watergate-scandal and the White House weddings of three first
daughters, Linda and Luci Johnson and Tricia Nixon.
   His pictures had appeared in several prominent magazines,
including Life, Look and The National Geographic. Several of his
Washington scenes were imprinted on the U.S. Postal Service's 1969
beautification stamps.
   The Stormlake, Iowa, native retired in 1974 and had been
operating his own firm since then.
   Knudsen died on Jan. 27 and is survived by his wife, two
daughters, two sons, two sisters and four grandchildren.
   
   dwc
</TEXT>
