<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-29 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Killed In Weekend Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sinhalese extremists raided
the house of a governing party official in a southern town and
stabbed him to death, officials said Sunday, raising to nine the
death toll in weekend violence.
   P.G. Munasinghe, a 47-year-old town council chairman and member
of the governing United National Party, was killed in his house in
Matale, 90 miles west of the capital, officials said.
   Meanwhile, extremists fatally shot two policemen and a civilian
in an ambush in two other southern towns and militants attacked
three police stations in or near the capital, killing four policemen
and a civilian, police said.
   The killings were blamed on the People's Liberation Front, a
militant Sinhalese group. A military official said the police
station attacks were aimed at frightening voters away from the polls
in next month's parliamentary election.
   ``It is apparently a psychological exercise to drive home the
point the Sinhalese subversives were quite capable of hitting city
police stations at their will,'' the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Ten candidates for the Feb. 15 election already have been killed
by radical groups opposed to the government. Eight have been blamed
on Sinhalese extremists, who oppose the Sihnalese-dominated
government's offer of limited autonomy to the minority Tamil
population that predominates in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   Police say two of the killings were the work of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, who have rejected the government's peace
overtures made under a peace accord brokered by neighboring India,
the region's military and political giant.
   A government communique said 15 suspected militants were arrested
Sunday during combined army and police searches after the overnight
raids on police stations.
   Officials of the Joint Operations Command, who cannot be
identified under briefing rules, said two soldiers and a civilian,
all Sinhalese, were fatally shot in Akuressa, 72 miles southwest of
Colombo.
   In the attacks on police stations, assailants wearing black
uniforms hurled grenades and homemade bombs before opening fire with
automatic rifles, Senaratne said. He said the gunmen escaped with
weapons but he gave no details.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the island nation's 16 million
people and dominate the government and the military. Tamils, who
account for 18 percent of the population, say they are discriminated
against by the Sinhalese.
</TEXT>
