<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietPoll     01-29 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Poll,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Enjoys Strong Support But Many Question Effect of Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll of 1,000 Moscow residents shows
overwhelming support for Mikhail Gorbachev's economic restructuring,
but when pressed, about half said the changes had no real impact on
their lives.
   The poll also indicated a majority of Moscow residents admit the
Soviet war in Afghanistan was a mistake and that former leader
Leonid Brezhnev was bad for the country, the Daily News said in its
Sunday editions.
   The poll, conducted by the Daily News along with five other news
organizations, shows Gorbachev's economic reforms enjoy a 93 percent
approval rating. But when pressed, 51 percent of those polled said
the reforms have had no real impact on their lives. And 17 percent
said the reforms were having a negative impact, the Daily News
reported.
   The poll also found that many Moscow residents are afraid to
venture out at night and that only 37 percent said they are very
proud to be Soviet citizens.
   The unprecedented poll was conducted in conjunction with WCBS
Radio and WCBS-TV in New York, WCVB-TV in Boston, KRON-TV in San
Francisco and the Detroit Free Press.
   The poll was conducted by the Soviet Institute of Sociology using
questions from the news organizations. The Boston polling firm of
Marttila &amp; Kiley, which conducted the U.S. end of the survey,
monitored the telephone interviews that took place between Dec. 12
and Dec. 21 and compiled the results. The pollsters reported a
margin of sampling error of 3.1 percentage points.
   On international relations, the poll indicated that Moscow
residents are overwhelmingly optimistic about the United States and
the Soviet Union getting along.
   Soviet experts said some of the results may not accurately
reflect attitudes, especially the overwhelming support for Gorbachev.
   ``We have no tradition of voicing public criticism of our
leaders,'' said Vladimier Andreyenkov of the Soviet Institute of
Sociology. ``Gorbachev's popularity is indeed high, but I would take
these figures with some reservations.''
   But the Moscow residents, 65 percent of them, rated former leader
Brezhnev unfavorably. And former dictator Josef Stalin received a 66
percent unfavorable rating.
   Another factor that may have influenced the answers of the Moscow
residents is that they were told at the start of questioning that
the poll was part of a joint U.S.-Soviet venture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
