<FIRST>r a AM-ArmeniaRelief     01-29 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenia Relief,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stars Sing For Quake Relief Record, TV Special</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainers Liza Minelli, Pia Zadora, Ben
Vereen, Irene Cara and Connie Stevens collaborated Sunday in the
making of a record and TV special to raise money for earthquake
victims in Soviet Armenia.
   ``We can do what we usually do in life to raise money,'' Miss
Minelli said before stepping into a recording studio at Paramount
Pictures Sunday afternoon. ``We can't do anything politically. When
I saw the disaster in Armenia I thought I was going to die.''
   The song ``For You, Armenia,'' was written by Charles Aznavour
and George Garvarentz and translated to English by Paul Williams.
Aznavour recorded the song for release in France with proceeds going
to quake aid.
   Reminiscent of the fund-raising effort of songs such as ``We Are
The World,'' most of the profit from ``For You, Armenia,'' will be
given to the Armenian Relief Society for direct donation to quake
victims.
   ``I've known Charles practically my whole life,'' Miss Minelli
said of Aznavour. ``When his people got into trouble, he mobilized.
I went to him and asked, `What can I do?' And he said, `Lift your
voice.'''
   Miss Minelli and such musicians as Ray Parker Jr., Steve
Lawrence, Juice Newton, members of the Doobie Brothers and Toto and
actor-singer David Soul headed a list of nearly 100 performers who
stood on platforms like a choir group as they rehearsed the song.
   The song will benefit victims who suffered from the devastation
that hit the Soviet-Turkish border last Dec. 7. The temblor measured
6.9 on the Richter scale of ground motion, killed about 25,000
people and left 500,000 homeless.
   ``The world is by your side. We know you will survive. For you
Armenia we've opened up our arms. You've opened up our hearts,'' the
song states.
   ``What this shows is that the entertainment business, in general,
can have a bigger effect on the world than once thought,'' said Miss
Newton. ``This is a real positive effect. It's a real plus to show
you care. Those people really need our help.''
   Actress Adrienne Barbeau, whose mother is Armenian, said she
jumped at the chance to participate.
   ``The only involvement I've been able to have so far is to donate
money and be here for this,'' she said.
   ``I see people reaching out with their hearts, minds and souls,''
said radio personality Casey Kasem. ``They want to repair the
world.''
   Aznavour said he wants the quake orphans to be well taken care of.
   ``I don't want to see the orphans go to other states because
they're the last of the culture,'' he said.
   Michael Masser and Joel Cohen are producing the record and Peter
Bogdonovich and Laszlo Kovacs will film the one-hour documentary and
music video. It was not immediately known which record company would
release the single.
   When asked how much money the record would raise Cohen said,
``Only God can determine that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
