<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Chess     01-29 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chess,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spraggett, Yusupov Draw Sixth Game; Match Goes Into Overtime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC CITY, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sixth game of the World Chess
Championship Candidates' quarterfinal between Kevin Spraggett of
Canada and Artur Yusupov of the Soviet Union was drawn on Sunday,
forcing the match into overtime.
   With the final score tied 3-3, a ``mini-match'' of two games will
be played. Yusupov will play with the advantage of white in the
first game on Tuesday.
   If a tie persists, a series of sudden-death tie-breakers played
at increasingly high speeds will be employed to break the deadlock.
   In Sunday's game, Spraggett, playing white, exchanged queens to
reach an endgame where he hoped to exploit Yusupov's weakened pawn
formation. But the Soviet grandmaster neutralized his opponent's
strategy with a pawn break on the 22nd move.
   In the final position, Yusupov has one pawn more, but its path is
blocked and neither side can make any progress.
   The winner of the Candidates, a series of knockout matches, will
challenge world champion Garri Kasparov for his title in 1990.
   In the seventh game, experts said the onus will be on Yusupov, a
28-year-old Muscovite who began the contest as clear favorite, to
achieve a decisive breakthrough.
   Spraggett, 34, from Montreal, may be content to avoid risks in
the next games, but go all-out in the sudden-death finish.
   In the previous stage of the competition, Spraggett knocked out
Soviet Grandmaster Andrei Sokolov in a nerve-wracking tie-breaker
where each players' thinking time was limited to 15 minutes for the
entire game.
   ``It's anybody's match now,'' said Canadian chess expert Larry
Bevand. ``Kevin has proved he can meet Yusupov and hold his own.''
   British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman is already through to the
semifinal of stage.
   The first game in the third quarterfinal, between Anatoly Karpov
of the Soviet Union and Johann Hjartarson of Iceland in Seattle,
Wash., ended in a draw Saturday.
   The fourth duel, between Dutch Grandmaster Jan Timman and Lajos
Portisch of Hungary, is scheduled to open in Antwerp, Belgium, on
Wednesday.
   A win scores one point and a draw a half point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
