<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Cuba     01-29 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Cuba,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro's Visit To Venezuela This Week Stirs Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some prominent leaders on Sunday called
Cuban President Fidel Castro a ``Caribbean Devil'' and a human
rights offender who should not have been invited to pay a visit this
week, his first in 30 years.
   Castro, along with over two dozen chiefs of state and high
government officials, including Vice President Dan Quayle, has
accepted an invitation to attend the inauguration Thursday of Social
Democratic President Carlos Andres Perez.
   Perez has said he will try to improve relations with Cuba but has
repeatedly said that ideological discrepancies between democratic
Venezuela and Marxist Cuba will remain insurmountable.
   ``Castro has been a factor of perturbation in the Caribbean,''
said Manuel Penalver, a leader of the governing Democratic Action
party. ``Venezuela does not win anything (with his visit). It rather
loses international credibility.''
   Penalver, who until last year was the party's secretary general
and represents the party's right wing, called Castro ``The Caribbean
Devil,'' saying the Cuban leader tried to impose a Marxist regime in
Venezuela.
   Castro visited Venezuela in 1959, shortly after toppling dictator
Fulgencio Batista. Castro received a warm welcome, but the open
support he later granted to Marxist guerrillas that plagued
Venezuela in the early 60s led Venezuela to break relations with
Havana.
   ``I don't quite understand the reasons for inviting Castro to the
ceremonies. I must express my personal dissatisfaction for inviting
a dictator who in 30 years has done nothing but trample Cubans'
human rights,'' said Monsignor Jorge Urosa Sabino, the Caracas
auxiliary bishop during a homily Saturday at a mass commemorating
136 years of the birth of Cuban hero Jose Marti.
   As president for the first time between 1974 and 1979, Perez
restored relations with Cuba, but diplomatic normalcy between both
countries did not last long.
   In 1980 they were on the brink of a total rupture again after a
Venezuelan military court acquitted anti-Castro leaders suspected of
blowing up a Cubana de Aviacion jetliner in 1976.
   Rightist deputy Vladimir Gessen, of the Democratic New Generation
party, also protested Castro's visit.
   ``The Caribbean dictator may have had some achievements. But also
Hitler, Mussolini, Stalin and Pinochet had some and it is not a
justification for their crimes,'' he said in a full-page
advertisement in the newspaper El Nacional on Sunday.
</TEXT>
