<FIRST>u a AM-UMW-Pittston 1stLd-Writethru a0692 01-29 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0692,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston, UMW Adopt Conciliatory Tone In Face Of Strike Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf, `They met...' to UDPATE with
meeting planned Monday. INSERTS one graf after 6th graf pvs, `We're in...'
to UPDATE with company president calling for quicker union response.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of anger and uncertainty, a
strike deadline looms at midnight Tuesday for 1,700 Appalachian coal
miners who have been on the job for Pittston Coal Group Inc. with no
contract.
   In recent days, Pittston and the United Mine Workers adopted a
conciliatory tone for the first time in the yearlong dispute, even
though neither side would predict that continuing talks might avert
a walkout in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky.
   The UMW issued statements last week that mentioned areas of
agreement. Pittston President Michael Odom said over the weekend
that the two sides were in ``substantial agreement'' on much of new
contract, although a half-dozen key sticking points remained.
   They met again Sunday in Washington to continue going over fine
points of a contract offer the union made Tuesday, in response to a
company offer made Nov. 9, company and union officials said.
   Pittston and the union planned another bargaining session Monday,
Odom said Sunday night.
   On Saturday, the governors of the three states said they had
asked UMW President Richard Trumka and the chairman of Pittston's
parent company, The Pittston Co., Paul Douglas, to try and avert a
strike, possibly by taking 30 to 60 days for each side to cool off.
   ``We're in total agreement with the governors that a strike is
senseless to their constituents and communities and the business
climate of the coal community,'' Odom said from his Abingdon home.
   Noting that the governors had asked the union for an immediate
reply, Odom said, ``I hoped they would have responded sooner.''
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said Saturday that before any decision
on putting off a strike would be made, Trumka would have to confer
with international union officers and elected district and local
officials.
   ``As we speak, there's a lot of momentum and people are preparing
for a strike,'' Corcoran said from his home in Silver Spring, Md.
``People are getting assignments and meetings are being set up.''
   Corcoran said top union officials will probably meet Monday to
discuss the governors' request.
   The labor dispute began last winter, when the companies of the
Bituminous Coal Operators Association agreed on a new contract with
miners for the second time in a row with no strike. Pittston had
dropped out of the the industry association, saying its business was
different from other major eastern producers and it required a
different type of contract.
   ``This company mines thin, deep metallurgical coal seams that
compete predominantly in the export market,'' Odom said. ``That
market is not protected by long-term price contracts. Every year,
you have to compete with the world competition.''
   Other major eastern coal producers enjoy long-term contracts with
domestic utilities, he said.
   Miners agreed to stay on the job with no contract after last Feb.
1 but each side repeatedly accused the other of hindering progress
in the contract talks.
   The UMW took miners off the job for a four-day ``memorial
period'' and then a six-day ``memorial period.''
   Pittston cut off health benefits to some 1,500 retirees, widows
and disabled miners, saying the benefits would have to be addressed
in a new contract. Several scattered wildcat strikes in Virginia and
West Virginia were believed spurred by retirees who set up picket
lines, company and union officials said.
   Pittston has vowed to operate through a strike and has advertised
for permanent replacement miners.
   New York analysts who follow the coal industry said last week
that the company will be able to operate through a strike, although
it might take several months to get up to full capacity.
   But the UMW has two unfair labor practices complaints pending
with the National Labor Relations Board and if the NLRB rules in
favor of the union, UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts said, miners
can strike in protest without fear of being permanently replaced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
