<FIRST>u a AM-HaitianDemonstration 1stLd-Writethru a0752 01-29 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian Demonstration, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0752,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haitians Protest Treatment Of Their Countrymen At Detention Facility</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT quote, `ready for war' sted `ready
from war.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people demonstrated Sunday outside a
federal detention center to protest the treatment of Haitian
immigrants held there.
   Inside the gates of the Immigration Service's Krome Avenue
Detention Center several dozen federal officers stood in closed
ranks, wearing shields, helmets, clubs and body armor.
   ``We come for peace, and they're ready for war,'' said Ray
Fauntroy, president of Dade County chapter of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference.
   The protesters were primarily Haitians. They carried placards
saying: ``Fight Racism. Justice For Black People'' and ``One black
is hurt, all are hurt.''
   The Haitians say people from their homeland are more likely to be
held for deportation than are white immigrants.
   Immigration officials have maintained that most Haitians entering
the United States are not eligible for asylum because they are
seeking economic refuge and not fleeing political persecution.
   The detention center, which is housing about 300 Haitians, was
placed under a modified lockdown _ severely restricting the movement
of detainees _ in preparation for the demonstration, officials said.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service district director Perry
Rivkind acknowledged earlier this month that the detention center
became seriously overcrowded with the arrival of 94 Haitians picked
up after their homemade sailboat ran aground in the Florida Keys.
   ``The more people at Krome, the longer they have to wait in line
for food and other things, the opportunity for protests and tension
grows,'' Rivkind said.
   Betty Ferguson, one of the speakers at the rally, mentioned the
riot-ready officers behind the fence, some of whom were armed.
   ``When they are ready to shoot us down like dogs, then that means
they know we are right,'' she said. ``We are only asking equal
treatment for Haitians.
   ``If they treat us like this and we're in the outside, how do you
think they're treating them on the inside?'' she asked.
   The demonstration was sponsored by the Haitian organization
Veye-Yo. Its members distributed leaflets listing the group's aims:
equal treatment for black refugees, freedom for the Haitians at
Krome and other installations around the nation, and no support for
any Haitian government linked to ousted dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier.
   Rev. Gerard Jean-Juste, director of the Haitian Refugee Center,
was among those in the crowd. ``We want equal treatment,'' he said.
``The Nicaraguans don't come here (to Krome). The Cubans don't stay
too long.''
</TEXT>
