<SECOND>AM-School Shooting,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Arrested As Second Suspect In School Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy surrendered to police Sunday
in connection with last week's shooting of four youngsters at a
Washington high school.
   The boy is the second person arrested in the shootings at Woodrow
Wilson High School. He surrendered shortly before noon Sunday and
was charged with assault with intent to kill, officials said.
   He is scheduled to be arraigned Monday in District of Columbia
Superior Court, police said. They would not reveal the youth's
identity, but said the teen-ager may be tried as an adult.
   The shootings occurred as students were leaving school Thursday.
A single assailant opened fire with an automatic weapon into a crowd
of students, wounding four, and then fled with at least one
accomplice in a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
   The wounded students were treated and released from area
hospitals.
   Police said they were investigating motives for the shootings,
but that the incident apparently was triggered by an argument
earlier in the day in the school cafeteria over a girl. They said
there were no indications that drugs were involved.
   Earlier, police arrested Rodney Reardon, 18, of Washington and
charged him with four counts of assault with intent to kill. Neither
he nor the 16-year-old arrested in the case attended Wilson High,
officials said.
