<FIRST>r a AM-AdulterousPreacher     01-29 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adulterous Preacher,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Back in Pulpit Three Years After Leaving in Disgrace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fundamentalist minister who left his
pulpit three years ago in disgrace after confessing to adultery
began preaching again Sunday, with forgiveness one of his themes.
   ``I have learned a lot of lessons. It's been a tough three
years,'' The Rev. Herman ``Buddy'' Frankland told about 50 people
gathered at the service held in a room rented at the Bangor Ramada
Inn. ``But I'm back because of your letters. ... My sins are under
the blood of Jesus Christ.''
   Frankland has stayed almost entirely out of the spotlight since
late 1985, when he left the Bangor Baptist Church after announcing
he had committed adultery.
   After he stepped down, a split occurred within the congregation,
prompting a fellow fundamentalist, the Rev. Jerry Falwell, to step
in as acting pastor to help reunite the church in 1986.
   In his services Sunday, Frankland talked about God's willingness
to forgive all sinners, even Ted Bundy, the serial killer who was
put to death in the electric chair last week.
   Frankland, no longer affiliated with Bangor Baptist Church, said
Sunday he was looking for a place he could rent for services in a
new church he called Messiah Temple.
   Asked after the sermon what prompted his return, Frankland said
he had received an inspiring letter from a former parishioner and
had felt guilty for having left his congregation.
   He acknowledged some people say he does not belong in Bangor but
he said, ``A shepherd should not leave his flock. I don't care what
people say.''
   Frankland founded the Bangor Baptist Church in 1966 and built it
into one of the largest in New England, with a reported membership
of 3,000 and with its own school and radio station.
</TEXT>
