<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionProtest     01-29 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protest,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protesters Kept in Jail For Refusing to Give Names</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nineteen abortion protesters
arrested at a clinic spent Sunday in jail after refusing to give
authorities their names, police said.
   The protesters were among 25 arrested Saturday at the Medical
Care Center at Woodbridge and charged with trespassing and
obstruction, Woodbridge police said.
   Eight of the demonstrators chained themselves together
neck-to-leg in the clinic's waiting room, while 17 others lay or sat
on the floor. At least 20 other protesters picketed and chanted
outside.
   It took police 12 hours to free all eight people from the
reinforced steel shackles and bars. Special equipment was brought in
from the New York City Police Department to grind through the metal.
   Ten women and 12 men spent Saturday night at the jail, said Sgt.
Charles Luizza. Three people gave police their names and addresses
and were released Sunday, he said.
   Bail initially was set at $500, but Municipal Judge Joseph
Dambach waived the bond if the protesters gave their names, Luizza
said.
   Last summer, hundreds of participants in an abortion protest
organized by a group called Operation Rescue overcrowded jails in
Atlanta by similarly refusing to give their names.
