<HEAD>Searchers Find No Trace of Missing Crab Boat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with boat not found by late Sunday;
identifies missing fishermen; picks up 6th graf pvs: `Meanwhile, the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers found no trace of a missing crab
fishing boat with six people aboard after searching the stormy Gulf
of Alaska, the Coast Guard said late Sunday.
   But the crew of a Japanese freighter was reported safe, officials
said.
   The crew of the 98-foot crabber Vestfjord, based in Seattle,
reported that its ship was sinking under the weight of accumulating
ice.
   The Vestfjord had been on a voyage from Seattle to Dutch Harbor
when it ran into 40-foot seas; wind blowing to 60 knots, or about 70
mph; and blowing snow, the Coast Guard said.
   Search aircraft went out in the dark early Sunday but could not
find the vessel because of the severe weather, the Coast Guard said.
   While search aircraft returned to their bases at nightfall, the
cutters Sedge and Morgenthau were to continue looking for the vessel
in the area, 30 miles south of the Trinity Islands. The Trinity
Islands are just south of Kodiak Island.
   Those aboard the missing boat were identified as the vessel's
skipper, Dic LaGary of Seattle; Kevin Melnick, 27, of Seattle;
William Hodgins, 33, of Anchorage; Richard Kristovish, 37, of
Seattle; Doug Harding, 35, of Seattle, and passenger Danny McDonald
of Seattle.
   The missing vessel was equipped with two life rafts, one of which
was equipped with an emergency locator beacon, the Coast Guard said.
No emergency beacon signals were picked up Sunday, the Coast Guard
said.
   Meanwhile, the Coast Guard called off its search for the crew
members of a Japanese cargo vessel when it was learned they still
were aboard their vessel.
   The 850-foot Port Star had called for help and was found by a
Navy aircraft. While the ship had lost much of its cargo in the
stormy seas, it still was afloat and heading for Japan, the Coast
Guard said.
   It had been believed that the crew of 20 had abandoned the vessel
some 300 miles southwest of Attu in the Aleutian Islands.
   The Port Star, owned by Nipponkai Steamship Co. of Tokyo, was
transporting logs.
</TEXT>
