<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing747s     01-29 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing 747s,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Announces Revised Delivery Schedule For 747s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co., which has been troubled by delays
in delivering its new 747-400 jumbo jet, plans to produce 57 747
jetliners in 1989, most of them in the second half of the year.
   The number was about what aerospace industry analysts had
predicted, even before Boeing was forced to rework its delivery
schedule.
   Boeing has said that problems with wiring and parts availability,
delays in certification, and an overly ambitious development and
production plan resulted in the delivery schedule being pushed back
three times in four months.
   The first model-400 was delivered Thursday to Northwest Airlines,
a month behind schedule.
   ``Although we regret having to revise delivery schedules, it is
most important to meet our traditional standards of quality and our
customers' high expectations for Boeing airplanes,'' Boeing
Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said Friday in a news
release.
   Company spokesman David Jimenez said the 57 projected deliveries
include all current models of 747s, but that the rescheduling
primarily involves the model-400, which will make up a majority of
the new planes.
   ``Delivery was to start in 1988 and go into 1989, with the
concentration of deliveries in the first half of the year,'' Jimenez
said. ``Now the concentration will be in the last half of 1989 and
extend to early 1990.
   ``A good part will take place at the end of the year, but we're
not going into specifics.''
   The new 747-400, the world's largest commercial jet, is capable
of carrying 412 passengers 8,400 miles nonstop, and up to 624
passengers on short-range flights. The plane has been extensively
redisigned, with a computerized cockpit that uses video display
screens to replace more than 600 lights, gauges and switches. The
plane can be flown by a crew of two, instead of the three needed on
earlier 747s.
   Boeing currently is producing about four 747s a month and plans
to increase production to about five per month by mid-1989. It had
hoped to deliver 31 747s in 1988, but actually delivered 24.
   In briefings with reporters last week, Phil Condit, Commercial
Airplanes executive vice president for engineering and production
declined to say what, if any, penalties Boeing would have to pay for
being late with the new 747s, which sell for approximately $125
million each.
   Boeing announced in October that it would be about one month late
with the first 20 747-400s. In December, deliveries were pushed back
further because of delays in getting Federal Aviation Administration
certification. Earlier this month, Boeing said it was once again
reviewing its delivery schedule.
   Bill Whitlow, an analyst with Dain Bosworth Co. in Seattle, said
the announcement was with the production range orignally expected.
   ``They're saying they're quite confident they'll be back on track
at some point during the year, and in terms of what the stock market
sees, it's a non-event because they had been projecting between 55
and 65 planes for the year,'' he said.
   He said that while some of the deliveries may slide into 1990,
the net number of planes delivered in 1989 will not change. Boeing
books payment for its aircraft upon delivery.
   Les Childress, an analyst with Harper McLean &amp; Co. in Seattle,
was taking more of a wait-and-see attitude.
   ``Boeing says that it'll deliver 57 planes, but saying that and
doing it are two different things,'' he said. ``They're telling
people they have their problems solved, but I'm not so sure they can
achieve that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
