<FIRST>u f AM-AutoDealers Bjt   01-29 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Dealers, Bjt,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audi Repairing Image, Exec Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi, the West German luxury automaker, is
trying to repair its dented image with dealers following the furor
over sudden acceleration by some of its cars. But whether the firm
is succeeding is a matter of opinion.
   Audi executives heard from their dealers in a closed meeting
Sunday during the National Automobile Dealers Association
convention, and there was less rancor at this gathering than at last
year's session, said Richard Mugg, vice president in charge of Audi
of America.
   Charges surfaced a few years ago that Audi 5000S automobiles
would accelerate without warning. Consumer groups suggested the
problem was in the car's design, but the company said drivers
stepping on the accelerator instead of the brake were to blame.
   Audi recalled the cars to install a device that prevents the
transmission from being shifted without applying the brake. Since
then, the federal government has received sudden acceleration
complaints from owners of a variety of other cars.
   ``We have a better understanding of each other,'' Mugg said after
meeting with the dealers. ``Last year at this time unintended
acceleration was the major problem and we've put that behind us.''
   But Audi dealer Ray Green of Jacksonville, Ill., disagreed.
   ``They still haven't overcome the stigma of sudden
acceleration,'' he said. If the controversy hadn't happened, Green
added, ``I would predict Audi would be selling more cars today.''
   Audi sales took a beating during 1988, falling 45 percent from
1987 levels. Recently, Audi sales have begun creeping back toward
year-ago figures. The company also has stopped selling the
5000-series cars in the United States.
   ``We had a difficult year phasing out our volume car _ the 5000 _
and replacing it with the 100 and 200,'' Mugg said.
   He added that in the middle of next month, Audi will begin an
image rebuilding campaign with the public and its dealers.
   Meanwhile, Green, who also is a Toyota dealer, said the Japanese
company made a mistake by requiring a separate dealership for its
new Lexus line of luxury cars.
   ``In my opinion, not letting the Toyota dealers have that
franchise is a big mistake,'' he said, adding that the company may
change its mind after Lexus dealerships are in operation for a few
years.
   ``When they see these dealers not making a profit, they will give
the dealers an entry-level vehicle,'' Green predicted.
   The Lexus, scheduled to go on sale this fall, varies in cost from
$20,000 to $40,000. It is aimed at buyers ready for luxury cars but
unwilling to pay more for European imports.
</TEXT>
