<FIRST>u f AM-DetroitNewspapers     01-29 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspaper Agency Announces Date For Implementation Of JOA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agency created to administer the proposed joint
operating agreement between the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit
News announced Sunday it would implement the partial merger on Feb.
6.
   The announcement came two days after a three-judge federal
appeals panel in Washington, D.C., upheld U.S. Attorney General
Edwin Meese's approval of the JOA and unanimously lifted a stay that
had been in effect prohibiting implementation of the agreement.
   The JOA would allow the newspapers to combine advertising,
circulation, production and other business operations to cut costs,
while keeping separate news and editorial departments.
   In light of Friday's decision, the management committee of the
Detroit Newspaper Agency agreed to implement the partial merger
barring further judicial stays prior to Feb. 6, said Alan Lenhoff,
assistant to Free Press Publisher David Lawrence Jr.
   Under the terms of the JOA, the merger of the newspapers'
business operations can begin on that date, the 10th day after the
appeals panel's decision.
   State Sen. John Kelly, head of the Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, said after Friday's appeals panel ruling that the
opposition group would make a decision on an appeal by Monday.
   The group either can request a hearing before the full 13-member
appellate court or appeal directly to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Telephone calls to Kelly's home and the home of W. Edward
Wendover, a newspaper publisher who is part of Kelly's group, went
unanswered Sunday afternoon.
   Sunday's announcement was made by William J. Keating, chief
executive of the Detroit Newspaper Agency; Louis A. Weil III, News
president and publisher; and Lawrence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
