<FIRST>r f AM-SaturnDealers     01-29 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saturn Dealers,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Announces First 26 Saturn Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 26 men picked up pens, signed their
names and on Sunday became the first franchised dealers for General
Motors Corp.'s Saturn subsidiary.
   The 26 dealers, located in large automobile-selling markets in 11
states, are the first of about 90 dealers who will begin selling
Saturn cars in fall 1990, said Donald Hudler, Saturn's vice
president for sales, service and marketing.
   Hudler estimated that each of the dealers invested $2 million to
$4 million to establish a new franchise. The businesses will be
separate from those already owned by the dealers.
   He also said dealers will be required to belong to marketing and
advertising associations. The next group of dealers will be
announced sometime in the late spring or early summer, Hudler said.
   The Saturn car has not been displayed publicly. Its assembly
plant is under construction in Spring Hill, Tenn. Hudler said Sunday
most of the buildings have been completed and the company is
equipping the plant now.
   In the fall of next year, Saturn will begin offering two
four-door models and one two-door car in the subcompact or compact
segment of the market. GM officials have said the car will compete
with imported cars.
</TEXT>
