<DOCNO> AP890129-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasEastern-Coastal     01-29 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Eastern-Coastal,0462</SECOND>
<UNK>Texas Eastern Board Rejects Coastal's $2.6 Billion Offer</UNK>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp.'s board of directors
unanimously rejected Sunday a $2.6 billion cash offer from Coastal
Corp., calling it ``clearly inadequate.''
   Coastal announced Jan. 16 it was making a cash tender offer of
$42 per share for all of Texas Eastern's outstanding common shares.
Since then, Texas Eastern's stock has soared, closing Friday at $48
a share.
   The tender offer is set to expire on Feb. 14.
   In a special board of directors meeting Sunday, Texas Eastern's
board was told by financial advisers they should wait for a better
offer.
   Dennis R. Hendrix, Texas Easten's president, said Coastal's offer
``is clearly inadequate.'' He said the board's action are designed
to protect shareholders from ``pressure tactics designed to stampede
them into a decision before they can service a better offer.''
   Hendrix added that the board's decision in no way prevents
Coastal from raising its bid.
   ``If there's only one short-fused bid on the table, shareholders
don't have a choice,'' Hendrix said in a prepared statement, ``they
have an ultimatum. It may be more than what they had, but we don't
believe it is the best they can get.''
   Coastal's president, James R. Paul, said in a statement, ``It's
obvious that after two weeks Texas Eastern still does not have a
better offer than coastal's $42 a share.''
   He said Coastal plans to respond and make further comment after
reviewing documents that Texas Eastern indicated it would file
Monday with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   In a court hearing last week in Houston, Texas Eastern officials
said the company might use a ``white knight'' to block the Coastal
bid and had a list of more than 50 possible buyers.
   Coastal officials later suggested that the comment was designed
to inflate stock prices and make their offer appear inadequate.
   Paul has said Coastal has asked Texas Eastern for information
that would justify a higher offer, but said the only response has
been ``rhetoric and a stonewall meeting last Sunday.'' Paul met with
Texas Eastern's board last weekend.
   Analysts have said they doubt that there may be a large number of
serious contenders to take over Texas Eastern, a Houston-based
natural gas company.
   Houston-based Enron Corp., which operates the nation's largest
natural gas transmission system and long had been considered a
possible candidate for a Texas Eastern takeover, will not say
whether it is talking to the company.
   During the court hearing before U.S. District Judge Lynn N.
Hughes, the judge denied a Texas Eastern request to delay a Feb. 7
hearing date in a Coastal lawsuit desinged to prevent Texas Eastern
from using anti-takeover measures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
